St. Martin's Church Rijmenam On this site stood a church or chapel built between 940 and 1050 which was replaced by a Gothic church in the 14th century. Figurative murals from that period are still visible in the left aisle. During the restoration of 2004, underfloor heating was installed (condition for restoring the church organ). The original oak portal was then demolished and replaced by a glass door and the marble tabernacle in the choir of the church was replaced by "wooden boxes". The oak seats for the notables have been removed. (source: wikipedia)

Rijmenam is a village located in the Belgian province of Antwerp and is part of the municipality of Bonheiden.The area around Rijmenam had been settled since the Roman era. A chapel has been known to exist since the 11th chapel. Rijmenam used to belong the Duchy of Brabant. In 1578, the Battle of Rijmenam was fought between the Dutch States Army and the Spanish forces over control of Mechelen. The village was almost complete destroyed, and rebuilt twenty years later. It used to be an agricultural community, but during the 20th century, it became a residential area.

Duffel is a railway station in the town of Duffel, Antwerp, Belgium. The station opened on 16 June 1836 on the Lines 25 and 27. The train services are operated by National Railway Company of Belgium .

Sint-Katelijne-Waver is a railway station in the town of Sint-Katelijne-Waver, Antwerp, Belgium. The station opened on 1 June 1865 on the Lines 25 and 27. The train services are operated by National Railway Company of Belgium .

Putte is a municipality located in the Belgian province of Antwerp. The municipality includes the towns of Putte, Beerzel, and the hamlets Grasheide and Peulis. The town of Putte is around 8 kilometres east of Mechelen. In 2021, Putte had a total population of 18,109. The total area is 34.96 km2.

The Rijmenam Bridge is a concrete girder bridge over the Dijle in Rijmenam, a borough of Bonheiden, in the Belgian province of Antwerp. The bridge consists of one span of 26.5 m, the width is 12.2 m. The bridge provides the connection from Rijmenam to Boortmeerbeek.
Already in 1906 there was a bridge over the Dijle here. This was then a cast iron girder bridge on two stone pillars in the river. In 1987 the current concrete bridge was built.

In 2012, the province of Antwerp completed construction of a flood plain along the Babbelsebeek in Kontich. This measure is part of a larger plan to protect the environment of the valley of the Lachene- and Babbelsebeek against flooding during extreme weather conditions. The construction of the Babbelse Lakes is a sustainable solution to prevent flooding in basements and gardens in the center of Lint. Some pond berms were constructed and banks were leveled to create more storage. The result is a green lung in the town of Kontich, maintained by volunteers of Natuurpunt and local farmers.

Author: Veleau | Fietsen langs water
More information

On the waterfront of the Nete, opposite the PIME, you will see a pumping station at the point where the Itterbeek flows into the Nete.

The water from the Itterbeek flows up to the dike and then flows gently through an adjustable lock with a non-return valve into the Nete. When there is an increased influx of water, the pumping station kicks into action and the water is spewed through the 2 large pipes into the Nete at a speed of 1,400 liters per second per pump. An impressive spectacle!

The pumping station was built after the severe floods of 1998, and was one of the province's measures to better protect the valley. The Itterbeek flows through an intensively built-up area, as a result of which part of the valley area has been taken over and can no longer be occupied by water. The source of the stream is in Beerzel, close to the highest point of the province of Antwerp, the Beerzelberg. Due to the large difference in height, the Itterbeek has to deal with large flows during heavy precipitation, causing the water to run downstream faster.

In addition to the pumping installation, the province has also constructed a large flood plain in Koningshooikt, the Jutse Plassen. This beautiful nature reserve is well worth a visit!

Bees are irreplaceable for pollination of flowers, plants and trees. By sharing our space with a beekeeper, we give the bees a place and strengthen an important link in our ecosystem. Without the bees, we can no longer grow and eat a lot of fruit and vegetables. But the bees are threatened by, among other things, the disappearance and fragmentation of nature, diseases and pests and the use of pesticides. From March we will place our first beehive in the garden. In this way we protect their survival and also our nature. The delicious honey they make is a nice extra that we get from it!

'Upcycle' is a term that is used when you are going to 'upgrade' waste into something that you can use again. Often it will get a completely new function. There are no real rules for it, all you need is a good dose of creativity. Our upcycle corner can be found at the large table in the cafeteria. In the 'upcycle' box you will find all kinds of waste and craft materials to get started with yourself. There are two books and sheets with examples. Have you finished your assignment and do you still have time left? Then test out how big your upcycle content is!

'Come and have a look inside to see more outside', vzw Natuurpunt invites the hiker. Here you will find all information about the Mechels Rivierengebied, including the Mechels Broek. The visitor center is located in a side street of the track between Muizen and Rijmenam, near the bridge over the Dijle in Muizen. There is only a small parking lot, so it is best to park along the road.

Muizen station is a 10-minute walk away. Every hour a train stops here from Leuven and Mechelen. You can also take city bus 3 in the direction of Muizen at Mechelen station and get off at the Brugstraat stop.

By bike you will find the Visitor Centre at junction 64 of Fietskaart 4 of the Fietsknooppuntennetwerk Provincie Antwerpen.

name.en: Chapel of St. Gummarus and St. Rumoldus

description.en:
Chapel originally located on the Mechelsebaan, see location on Popp map (third quarter of the 19th century), but demolished when the road was widened in 1971 and rebuilt according to the original appearance with old brick on the Stormschranslaan. Presumably built by the abbess of Rozendaal or her tenant on the Stormschranshoeve in 1688 at the place where Sint-Rumoldus and Sint-Gummarus met, as evidenced by an inscription in the 17th century. Chapel on rectangular plan with three-sided closure under gable roof (ridge perpendicular to the street, artificial slates). Gabled gable with shoulder pieces and crowning iron cross. Pointed arch door with imposts. Source: https://inventaris.onroerenderfgoed.be/erfgoedobjecten/2708

Author: Rudy Wuyts
More information

"Kasteeltje van Perwijsbroeck", modo "Castle of Coorebijter" after a Brussels family that lived in it for a long time (1901-1933) as a country estate. Built circa 1850 on the site of an earlier redoubt from the Spanish era, to guard the nearby Nete crossing; Within the earthen ramparts were barracks, a prison and a chapel. After the peace of Munster in 1648, the redoubt gave way to dwellings; the lands came into the hands of Johannes Baptist Van Holen, tax collector at Duffel; In 1849-1850 he had the houses demolished and replaced by a country house, a garden with pond, fenced on the street side with iron fence, was laid out to the south. Repaired after the heavy war damage of 1914 and purchased in 1933 by the municipality, which sold the mansion again after two years, but converted the garden, laid out in the second half of the 19th century, as a municipal park in 1934/6; the construction on the English model includes red horse chestnut, marsh cypress and fern beech. The open space to the north and northwest was transformed into parking. Source: https://inventaris.onroerenderfgoed.be/erfgoedobjecten/2601

Author: Rudy Wuyts
More information

Located in a park with a preserved moat. Former farm in 1874, (W. Van Hoof) or 1877 (P. Diriken) converted into a castle, donated in 1900 to the poor board of the municipality as a home for the elderly, but the property was sold in 1903 and with the proceeds the old people's home was founded in the Wilsonstraat in 1908. Destroyed during the First World War and then rebuilt and modified several times, it is said to have preserved the foundations of the former castle. Eclectic country house of one + two storeys with staggered volumes under a slate roof. Cemented plinth and bands, rectangular and arched wall openings. Perpendicular gardener's house to the southwest. Access bridge with preserved iron fence between bluestone posts. In the surrounding park there may be an ice cellar to the west of the house. Source: https://inventaris.onroerenderfgoed.be/erfgoedobjecten/3220
